{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17418452","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17418452"},"attributes":{"position":4,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T10:35:32+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T10:35:32+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":{"type":"questionSessions","id":"1261514"}},"session":{"data":{"type":"questionSessions","id":"1261514"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1415"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}},{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17496768","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17496768"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T08:55:53+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T08:55:53+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1415"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questionSessions","id":"1261514","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionSessions/1261514"},"attributes":{"startedAt":"2025-09-28T10:35:00+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-28T10:36:42+09:30","sessionType":"qbank","questionStatus":"all","difficulty":[],"timeLimit":null,"questionCount":7,"questionsAnswered":6,"marksTotal":6,"marksAttainable":6,"marksAttempted":6,"finishedAt":"2025-09-28T10:35:40+09:30","resultsAvailable":true,"score":0,"questionsCorrect":0,"marksCorrect":0},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"pack":{"data":{"type":"packs","id":"5"}},"exam":{"data":null}}},{"type":"questions","id":"1415","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1415"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.19,0.03,0.11,0.54,0.13]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1415"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"35825"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1415","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1415"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1415"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"20653"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"4965"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"502"},{"type":"contributions","id":"1597"},{"type":"contributions","id":"2480"},{"type":"contributions","id":"45786"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"35825","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/35825"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 74-year-old woman presents to her regular GP reporting fatigue, malaise and generalised weakness for several weeks. She denies fevers, shortness of breath or other constitutional symptoms. She does not know if her exercise tolerance has changed recently. Her existing medical conditions were previously well managed, with her GP recently commencing her on allopurinol one month ago after a new diagnosis of gout.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EMedical History:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAutoimmune aortitis\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAsthma\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EGout\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHistory of unprovoked DVT/PE\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EMedications:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAzathioprine + prednisolone (long term)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESalbutamol (PRN)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAllopurinol\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWarfarin\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe GP decides to order some initial blood tests, which show a haemoglobin of 62g/L (120-160) and a leukocytopaenia.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely cause of her bicytopaenia?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Long term prednisolone use","Anaemia due to occult blood loss","Malignancy","Drug interaction with new allopurinol","Anaemia of chronic disease"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EAzathioprine is a bone marrow suppressant used to treat an array of autoimmune diseases. It achieves this by firstly being metabolised to 6-mercaptopurine which then exerts its effects on suppressing the marrow. Xanthine oxidase then further metabolises 6-mercaptopurine into inactive products.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAllopurinol, however, is a xanthine oxidase inhibitor. Hence, when used concomitantly with azathioprine results in raised levels of the active 6-mercaptopurine and hence increased toxicity on the marrow leading to significant myelosuppression. Thus, by inhibiting xanthine oxidase the toxicity of azathioprine is increased, leading to cytopaenia and further immunosuppression. \u003Cstrong\u003EDrug interaction\u003C/strong\u003E has occurred. As a result, patients can develop anaemia and increased susceptibility to infection.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhilst this question demonstrates a bicytopaenia, pancytopaenia is also common and patients can become thrombocytopaenic where all 3 cell lines are affected.\u0026nbsp;\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe advice is to cease the xanthine oxidase inhibitor, but if unable to do so, the dose of azathioprine should be reduced to 25% of the intended dose and her blood picture closely monitored.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["When starting a patient on a new drug, consideration must always be given to medications already being used by that patient and the possibility of drug interactions."],"references":["Gearry RB, Day AS, Barclay ML, et al. Azathioprine and allopurinol: A two-edged interaction. J Gastroenterol Hepatol. 2010;25(4):653\u2013655."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"20653"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1415"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"20653","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/20653"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2023-05-09T17:18:16+09:30","updatedAt":"2023-05-09T17:18:16+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1415"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"35825"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4965","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4965"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Haematological Presentations","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":"2024-10-17T23:22:36+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-10-17T23:22:36+10:30"},"relat